// Overcoming Temptation — Grace Daily devotional plan content
// Source: Bao's book "Overcoming Temptation" (faithdailywalk.com). Scripture: KJV (public domain).
// title, scripture, walk, prayer, oneThing, reflect = exact book text, untouched (Tiff-blessed).
// Anchor verse: 1 Corinthians 10:13 / James 4:7 (KJV). Four-week arc: Understanding Temptation / The Faithfulness of God / The Weapons of Victory / Victory Through Christ.

const PLAN_TEMPTATION = [
  {
    day: 1,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "No Temptation but Common to Man",
    ref: "1 Corinthians 10:13",
    scripture: "There hath no temptation taken you but such as is common to man: but God is faithful, who will not suffer you to be tempted above that ye are able; but will with the temptation also make a way to escape, that ye may be able to bear it.",
    walk: `Friend, we begin our journey with the very verse that anchors this book, and it is full of hope for anyone weary of the battle against temptation. In a single verse, Paul gives us three great truths that reframe the entire fight: our temptation is common, our God is faithful, and there is always a way of escape. Let these three truths sink deep into your heart today, for they are the foundation of all the victory we will explore.

Consider the first truth: *There hath no temptation taken you but such as is common to man.* Your temptation, whatever it is, is common to man. It is not unique to you, not a sign that you are uniquely broken or uniquely sinful. The very temptation you face has been faced by countless others; it is common to the human experience. This is freeing, friend, because temptation often comes wrapped in a lie that whispers, *you are the only one who struggles with this; you are uniquely weak; no one else fails like you do.* But Paul says your temptation is common to man. You are not alone in it, not uniquely defeated by it. It is a common struggle, and there is a common victory.

Consider the second truth: *but God is faithful, who will not suffer you to be tempted above that ye are able.* God is faithful, and His faithfulness sets a limit on your temptation. He will not allow you to be tempted beyond what you are able to bear. This does not mean temptation will be easy, but it means it will never be more than you can bear with the help God provides. The faithful God stands over your every temptation, setting a limit, ensuring that you are never tempted above what you are able. You may feel overwhelmed, but God's faithfulness guarantees that the temptation is not, in fact, beyond your ability to overcome in His strength.

And consider the third truth: *but will with the temptation also make a way to escape, that ye may be able to bear it.* With every temptation, God makes a way of escape. There is always a way out, friend, always a path of escape that God Himself provides. You are never trapped, never without an exit, never left with no choice but to sin. With every temptation, God provides a way to escape it and to bear it. The way out may not always be obvious, but it is always there, for God has promised to provide it. Our task is to look for the way of escape God has made, and to take it.

So begin your journey with these three truths firmly in hand, friend. When temptation comes, remember: it is common to man, so you are not uniquely defeated. God is faithful, so you will not be tempted above what you are able. And God makes a way of escape, so you are never trapped without a way out. These truths reframe the entire battle against temptation. You are not fighting alone, not fighting beyond your ability, not fighting without a way of escape. You are fighting alongside a faithful God who limits your temptation and provides your escape. So take heart, friend, and let these truths be the foundation of the victory we will build together over these thirty days. There is a way of escape, provided by a faithful God. Look for it, and take it.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for the hope of this verse. When temptation makes me feel uniquely weak and alone, remind me that it is common to man. When I feel overwhelmed, remind me that You are faithful and will not let me be tempted above what I am able. And when I feel trapped, help me to look for the way of escape You have promised to provide. Let these three truths be the foundation of my victory: my temptation is common, You are faithful, and there is always a way out. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, hold these three truths ready for the moment temptation comes: it is "common to man," God is "faithful," and He provides "a way to escape." When tempted, look actively for the way out God has provided, and take it.`,
    reflect: `Which of the three truths, that temptation is common, that God is faithful, or that He provides a way of escape, do you most need to believe right now? How does looking for the "way to escape" change the way you face temptation?`,
  },
  {
    day: 2,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "Watch and Pray",
    ref: "Matthew 26:41",
    scripture: "Watch and pray, that ye enter not into temptation: the spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak.",
    walk: `Friend, here Jesus gives His disciples, and us, a vital strategy for dealing with temptation before it overwhelms us: *Watch and pray, that ye enter not into temptation.* Jesus spoke these words in the garden of Gethsemane, urging His sleepy disciples to be alert and prayerful in the hour of trial. And His words give us two essential practices for overcoming temptation: watching and praying. These are not practices for the moment of crisis only, but ways of life that guard us before temptation overwhelms us.

Consider the first practice: *Watch.* To watch is to be alert, vigilant, on guard, aware of the danger of temptation rather than careless and complacent. So often we fall into temptation because we are not watching, not alert to the danger, caught off guard. We drift through life unaware of the traps around us, the situations that will tempt us, the weaknesses the enemy will exploit. But Jesus calls us to watch, to be vigilant, to be aware of where temptation is likely to come and to guard against it. The watchful believer sees temptation coming and prepares for it, rather than being ambushed by it.

Consider the second practice: *pray.* Alongside watching, we are to pray, asking God for help, for strength, for deliverance from temptation. We cannot overcome temptation in our own strength; we need God's help, and prayer is how we lay hold of that help. Jesus taught us to pray, *lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil,* and here He urges His disciples to pray that they enter not into temptation. The praying believer brings the battle to God, asking for the strength and deliverance that only God can give. Watching makes us alert to the danger; praying lays hold of God's help against it.

And see the purpose of these practices: *that ye enter not into temptation.* The goal is to deal with temptation before it overwhelms us, to keep from entering into it in the first place. This is wisdom, friend. It is far easier to avoid temptation than to escape it once we are in its grip. By watching and praying, we deal with temptation at a distance, guarding against it before it overtakes us, rather than waiting until we are caught in its full force. The watchful, praying believer keeps from entering into temptation, dealing with it before it becomes overwhelming.

And see the reason Jesus gives for this vigilance: *the spirit indeed is willing, but the flesh is weak.* Jesus understands our condition. Our spirit may be willing, sincerely desiring to do right and overcome temptation, but our flesh is weak, prone to fail when tested. Because of this weakness, we cannot afford to be careless or self-confident; we must watch and pray, knowing our own weakness and our need for God's help. So take up these two practices, friend, watching and praying, not merely in the moment of crisis, but as a way of life. Be alert to the danger of temptation, and bring the battle to God in prayer. For the spirit is willing but the flesh is weak, and the watchful, praying believer deals with temptation before it overwhelms, guarding against entering into it in the strength God provides.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me to watch and pray, that I enter not into temptation. Help me to be alert and vigilant, aware of where temptation is likely to come, rather than careless and caught off guard. And help me to pray, bringing the battle to You and laying hold of Your help, for I cannot overcome in my own strength. I know that my spirit may be willing, but my flesh is weak. So teach me to watch and pray as a way of life, dealing with temptation before it overwhelms me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, practice watching and praying. Identify one situation where temptation is likely to come, watch for it with alertness, and pray in advance for strength, dealing with the temptation before it overwhelms you.`,
    reflect: `Where have you been careless rather than watchful, caught off guard by temptation? How might watching (staying alert to danger) and praying (laying hold of God's help) keep you from "entering into" temptation in the first place?`,
  },
  {
    day: 3,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "Drawn Away by Our Own Lust",
    ref: "James 1:14",
    scripture: "But every man is tempted, when he is drawn away of his own lust, and enticed.",
    walk: `Friend, here James helps us understand how temptation actually works within us, and it is essential knowledge for the battle: *every man is tempted, when he is drawn away of his own lust, and enticed.* Temptation works by drawing us away through our own desires, enticing us with the promise of satisfying some craving within us. Understanding this inner mechanism of temptation helps us see where the real battle lies, not merely in the outward enticement, but in our own inward desires.

Consider what James says about the source of our temptation: *drawn away of his own lust.* The word *lust* here means strong desire or craving. James is saying that temptation works by appealing to our own desires, our own cravings, the things we want. The outward temptation, whatever it is, gains its power by connecting to some desire within us, drawing us away through that desire. This is an important insight, friend. Temptation is not merely an external force that overpowers us against our will; it works by appealing to desires that are already within us, drawing us away through our own cravings.

And see the two-step process James describes: *drawn away... and enticed.* First we are drawn away, our desire pulling us toward the temptation, away from the path of obedience. Then we are enticed, lured in, hooked, as the temptation promises to satisfy our craving. The image is almost like fishing, friend, where bait is used to entice a fish, drawing it toward the hook through its own hunger. Temptation works similarly, using the bait of some promised satisfaction to entice us, drawing us toward sin through our own desires. We are drawn away by desire and enticed by the promise of its fulfillment.

Now why is it important to understand this, friend? Because it shows us where the real battle lies. If temptation were merely an external force, the battle would be entirely outside us. But because temptation works by appealing to our own desires, the battle is largely within, in the realm of our desires and cravings. This means that overcoming temptation involves more than just avoiding external triggers, important as that is; it involves dealing with the desires within us that temptation appeals to. The real battle against temptation is fought, in large part, in the realm of our own hearts and desires.

So understand how temptation works, friend, that you might fight it where the battle truly lies. Recognize that temptation gains its power by appealing to your own desires, drawing you away and enticing you through your own cravings. This means the battle is not merely external but internal, in the realm of your desires. So as you fight temptation, do not only guard against external triggers, but bring your desires themselves to God, asking Him to transform them, to give you new and holy desires that will not be so easily drawn away. The deepest victory over temptation comes not merely from resisting the external enticement, but from having our desires themselves changed and reordered by God, so that we are no longer so easily drawn away by our own lust. So bring your desires to God, friend, and let Him do His transforming work, that the very cravings temptation appeals to might be brought under His lordship.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You help me understand that temptation works by drawing me away through my own desires, enticing me with the promise of satisfying some craving within me. Help me to see that the real battle is largely within, in the realm of my desires. So I bring my desires to You, Lord. Transform them. Give me new and holy desires that will not be so easily drawn away. Reorder the cravings within me, that I might not be so easily enticed, and bring my very desires under Your lordship. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, recognize that temptation works by appealing to your own desires. Rather than only guarding against external triggers, bring a specific desire that temptation exploits to God, asking Him to transform and reorder it.`,
    reflect: `How does understanding that temptation works by "drawing away" your own desires change where you see the battle? What desire within you does temptation tend to appeal to, and what would it mean to bring that desire to God for transformation?`,
  },
  {
    day: 4,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "When Lust Hath Conceived",
    ref: "James 1:15",
    scripture: "Then when lust hath conceived, it bringeth forth sin: and sin, when it is finished, bringeth forth death.",
    walk: `Friend, James continues from yesterday by tracing the full progression of temptation, showing us where it leads if it is not stopped: *when lust hath conceived, it bringeth forth sin: and sin, when it is finished, bringeth forth death.* This is a sobering verse, naming the deadly end of unchecked temptation. But James does not name this progression to leave us in despair; he names it to wake us up, to show us why we must stop temptation early, before it runs its deadly course.

Consider the progression James traces. It begins with lust, the desire we saw yesterday. Then *when lust hath conceived, it bringeth forth sin.* When the desire is entertained, nurtured, allowed to grow rather than being resisted, it conceives and brings forth sin; the inward desire becomes the outward act. And then *sin, when it is finished, bringeth forth death.* Sin, when it is full-grown, allowed to run its course, brings forth death, separation from God, destruction, ruin. This is the deadly progression of temptation unchecked: from desire, to sin, to death. It is a sobering picture, friend, of where temptation leads if it is not stopped.

Now I want to handle this sobering verse with care, friend, the same care we would want for any hard truth. James names this deadly progression not to crush us with despair, not to leave us hopeless under the weight of sin's seriousness, but to wake us up to the danger and drive us to stop temptation early. The seriousness of sin's end is meant to motivate us, not to paralyze us. And the whole rest of this book is about the victory and the way of escape God provides, so that this deadly progression need not run its course in our lives. James names the danger to drive us to the deliverance.

See the key insight in this progression, friend: temptation must be stopped early, before it runs its course. The progression from desire to sin to death is not inevitable; it can be stopped, and the earlier it is stopped, the better. If we resist the desire at the beginning, before it conceives, we stop the progression before it produces sin. This is why dealing with temptation early, at the level of desire, is so important. Once desire has conceived and brought forth sin, the progression is much harder to stop. But caught early, at the level of the first desire, the deadly progression can be halted before it begins.

So let this sobering verse wake you up, friend, not to despair, but to vigilance. Understand the deadly progression of temptation unchecked, from desire, to sin, to death, and let it motivate you to stop temptation early, at the level of the first desire, before it conceives and brings forth sin. Do not entertain the desire, nurse it, allow it to grow, for that is how it conceives and brings forth sin. Instead, resist it early, bring it to God, take the way of escape, and stop the progression before it begins. And remember, friend, that this whole book is about the victory God provides, so that this deadly progression need not have the final word in your life. The seriousness of sin's end is real, but so is the way of escape, and the victory, and the grace of God. So be sober about where temptation leads, but be hopeful about the deliverance God provides, and stop temptation early, in the strength He gives.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You show me the deadly progression of temptation unchecked: from desire, to sin, to death. Let this sobering truth wake me up to the danger, not crush me with despair. Help me to stop temptation early, at the level of the first desire, before it conceives and brings forth sin. Keep me from entertaining and nursing desires that lead to sin and death. And thank You that You have provided a way of escape and a victory, so that this deadly progression need not run its course in my life. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, resolve to stop temptation early, at the level of the first desire, rather than entertaining and nursing it until it "conceives" and brings forth sin. Catch one tempting desire at its very beginning and bring it to God.`,
    reflect: `How does understanding the progression from "lust" to "sin" to "death" motivate you to stop temptation early? Why is it so much easier to halt temptation at the level of the first desire than after it has "conceived"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 5,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "The Lust of the Flesh",
    ref: "1 John 2:16",
    scripture: "For all that is in the world, the lust of the flesh, and the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life, is not of the Father, but is of the world.",
    walk: `Friend, here John helps us understand the landscape of temptation by naming three great channels through which the world tempts us: *the lust of the flesh, and the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life.* Understanding these three channels helps us recognize temptation in its various forms, so that we are not caught off guard by its different disguises. Let us consider each, that we might know the terrain of the battle we fight.

Consider the first channel: *the lust of the flesh.* This is the temptation to gratify our bodily appetites and desires in wrong ways, the cravings of the flesh for forbidden pleasures, indulgences, and satisfactions. The lust of the flesh tempts us through our physical desires, urging us to satisfy them outside the bounds God has set. This is one of the most common and powerful channels of temptation, friend, appealing to the strong desires of the body. Recognizing it for what it is helps us to be on guard against its pull.

Consider the second channel: *the lust of the eyes.* This is the temptation that comes through what we see, the craving for what is visually appealing, the coveting of what our eyes behold. The lust of the eyes tempts us to want what we see, to covet possessions, to be drawn toward what looks desirable. So much temptation enters through the eyes, friend, through what we look at and are drawn to. Recognizing this channel helps us to guard our eyes, knowing that what we behold can become a doorway to temptation.

Consider the third channel: *the pride of life.* This is the temptation toward self-exaltation, status, boasting, the proud craving for recognition, importance, and the glory of this life. The pride of life tempts us to exalt ourselves, to seek our own glory, to take pride in our position and possessions and achievements. This channel is subtler than the others, friend, for it works through our pride rather than our bodily appetites. But it is no less a channel of temptation, drawing us toward the self-exaltation that opposes God.

And see what John says about all three: *is not of the Father, but is of the world.* These three channels of temptation are not of the Father; they belong to the world, to the fallen system that opposes God. This is important to recognize, friend. The lust of the flesh, the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life all come not from God but from the world, and they lead us away from the Father. None of these channels carries anything that originates with God or draws us closer to Him; each belongs to the world and pulls us away from the Father who loves us.

It is worth noticing, too, that these same three channels appear at the very beginning, in the temptation of Eve in the garden. She saw that the tree was good for food, the lust of the flesh; that it was pleasant to the eyes, the lust of the eyes; and that it was desirable to make one wise, the pride of life. The same three channels appeared in the wilderness when the tempter came to Jesus, urging Him to turn stones to bread, offering Him the kingdoms of the world, and tempting Him to throw Himself down for display. The channels are ancient and consistent, friend, and recognizing them helps us see temptation for what it is, in whatever form it takes.

So as you fight temptation, recognize it in its various forms, the lust of the flesh, the lust of the eyes, the pride of life, and know that none of it is of the Father. Knowing the terrain of the battle helps you to be on guard against temptation in all its disguises, recognizing it whether it comes through bodily appetite, through what you see, or through pride. So watch all three channels, friend, and do not be caught off guard by any of temptation's various forms.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You help me understand the landscape of temptation by naming its three channels: the lust of the flesh, the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life. Help me to recognize temptation in all these forms, whether it comes through my bodily appetites, through what I see, or through my pride, so that I am not caught off guard by its various disguises. And remind me that none of this is of You, but of the world. Guard me against temptation in all its channels, and keep me close to You, my Father. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, watch for temptation in all three of its channels: the lust of the flesh (bodily appetites), the lust of the eyes (craving what you see), and the pride of life (self-exaltation). Recognize which channel tempts you most, and guard against it.`,
    reflect: `Which of the three channels, the lust of the flesh, the lust of the eyes, or the pride of life, tends to tempt you most? How does recognizing temptation's various disguises help you guard against being caught off guard?`,
  },
  {
    day: 6,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "Sin Lieth at the Door",
    ref: "Genesis 4:7",
    scripture: "If thou doest well, shalt thou not be accepted? and if thou doest not well, sin lieth at the door. And unto thee shall be his desire, and thou shalt rule over him.",
    walk: `Friend, these were God's words to Cain, spoken in warning before Cain committed the first murder, and they give us a vivid picture of the nature of temptation and our call to master it: *sin lieth at the door. And unto thee shall be his desire, and thou shalt rule over him.* Sin is pictured as a crouching predator, lying at the door, desiring to have us, and yet God tells Cain that he must, and can, rule over it. Here is both a sobering warning and an empowering call.

Consider the picture God paints: *sin lieth at the door.* Sin is pictured as a beast crouching at the door, lying in wait, ready to pounce. This is a vivid image of temptation, friend, as something active, predatory, waiting for its opportunity to overtake us. Sin is not passive; it lies in wait, crouching at the door, ready to spring upon us when we are vulnerable. This warning was given to Cain when his countenance had fallen, when anger and jealousy were rising in his heart, and God warned him that sin was crouching, ready to overtake him. The picture warns us to take temptation seriously, as an active predator lying in wait.

And see the desire of this crouching sin: *unto thee shall be his desire.* Sin desires to have us, to master us, to overtake and control us. The crouching predator desires its prey; sin desires to dominate us, to rule over us, to make us its slave. This is the aim of temptation, friend, not merely to trip us up once, but to master us, to gain control, to rule over us. Temptation seeks our enslavement, desiring to have us and to dominate us. This is a sobering reality, reminding us of what is at stake in the battle against temptation: not merely a single failure, but the danger of being mastered by sin.

But see the empowering call God gives: *and thou shalt rule over him.* Though sin desires to master us, God tells Cain that he must, and can, rule over it. This is the call to master temptation rather than being mastered by it. Sin desires to rule over us, but we are called to rule over sin. This is an empowering word, friend, for it tells us that we are not helpless before temptation, doomed to be mastered by it. We are called, and enabled, to rule over it, to master it, to refuse to let it dominate us. The crouching predator desires to have us, but we may rule over it.

So take temptation seriously, friend, as the crouching predator it is, but do not be mastered by it; rule over it. Recognize that sin lies at the door, active and predatory, desiring to master you and make you its slave. But hear God's empowering call: you shall rule over it. You are not helpless before temptation, not doomed to be mastered by it. By God's strength, you are called and enabled to rule over sin, to master temptation rather than being mastered by it. Sadly, Cain did not heed this call, and sin mastered him. But the call remains for us, friend, and the strength to fulfill it is found in God. So take up the call to rule over sin, in the strength God provides, refusing to let the crouching predator master you. For though sin desires to have you, you shall, by God's grace, rule over it.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You warn me that sin lies at the door like a crouching predator, desiring to master me and make me its slave. Help me to take temptation seriously, recognizing its predatory desire to rule over me. But thank You for the empowering call: that I shall rule over it. I am not helpless before temptation, doomed to be mastered by it. By Your strength, help me to rule over sin, to master temptation rather than being mastered by it. Give me the strength to heed Your call where Cain did not. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take seriously that sin "lieth at the door" like a crouching predator desiring to master you, but take up God's empowering call: "thou shalt rule over him." In God's strength, refuse to be mastered by a temptation, ruling over it instead.`,
    reflect: `How does the picture of sin "crouching at the door," desiring to master you, help you take temptation seriously? How does God's call, "thou shalt rule over him," empower you to master temptation rather than be mastered by it?`,
  },
  {
    day: 7,
    week: 1,
    weekTitle: "Understanding Temptation",
    title: "Your Adversary the Devil",
    ref: "1 Peter 5:8",
    scripture: "Be sober, be vigilant; because your adversary the devil, as a roaring lion, walketh about, seeking whom he may devour.",
    walk: `Friend, we close this first week on understanding temptation by naming the enemy behind much of it: *your adversary the devil, as a roaring lion, walketh about, seeking whom he may devour.* Behind the temptations we face stands a real adversary, the devil, who actively seeks our destruction. Peter calls us to be sober and vigilant in light of this enemy. Understanding that we have a real adversary helps us take the battle seriously and stay on guard.

Consider the call Peter gives: *Be sober, be vigilant.* In light of the enemy he is about to name, Peter calls us to be sober, clear-minded and self-controlled, and vigilant, watchful and alert. This echoes the watching Jesus called for in the garden. We are to be sober and vigilant because we have a real adversary who seeks our destruction. We cannot afford to be careless, drowsy, or complacent, for the enemy is active and seeking to devour us. The call to sobriety and vigilance is a call to take the spiritual battle seriously, staying alert and clear-minded in the face of a real and active enemy.

And see the enemy Peter names: *your adversary the devil.* We have an adversary, an enemy who opposes us, and it is the devil. This is sobering but important to understand, friend. Behind much of the temptation we face stands a real, personal adversary, the devil, who actively works for our downfall. Temptation is not merely an impersonal force or our own weakness; there is an enemy behind much of it, an adversary who seeks our ruin. Recognizing that we have a real adversary helps us understand the nature of the battle and take it seriously.

And see how Peter describes this adversary: *as a roaring lion, walketh about, seeking whom he may devour.* The devil is pictured as a roaring lion, prowling about, seeking prey to devour. This is a vivid and sobering picture, friend, of an active, dangerous, predatory enemy. The devil is not passive; he walks about, actively seeking whom he may devour, looking for those he can overcome and destroy. This reminds us of the seriousness of the battle and our need for vigilance. We have a roaring lion as our adversary, prowling about, seeking to devour us. We dare not be careless before such an enemy.

But take heart, friend, even as we name this enemy. We do not name the adversary to fill you with fear, but to help you take the battle seriously and stay on guard. And remember that, as we will see in the weeks ahead, this roaring lion is a defeated enemy, conquered by Christ, who can be resisted and made to flee. So be sober and vigilant, friend, recognizing that you have a real adversary, the devil, who as a roaring lion seeks to devour you. Take the battle seriously; do not be careless or complacent before such an enemy. But do not be paralyzed by fear either, for the enemy you face has been defeated by Christ, and in His strength you can resist the devil and stand firm. So close this week of understanding temptation with clear eyes: you have a real enemy, but you have a greater Savior. Be sober, be vigilant, and stand firm in the strength of the One who has overcome the roaring lion.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me to be sober and vigilant, because I have a real adversary, the devil, who as a roaring lion walks about seeking whom he may devour. Help me to take this battle seriously, staying alert and clear-minded, not careless or complacent before such an enemy. But keep me from being paralyzed by fear, for I know that this roaring lion is a defeated enemy, conquered by Christ. Help me to stand firm in Your strength, resisting the adversary in the power of the One who has overcome him. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, be "sober" and "vigilant," recognizing that you have a real adversary who seeks your destruction. Take the spiritual battle seriously and stay on guard, while resting in the truth that this enemy has been defeated by Christ.`,
    reflect: `How does recognizing that you have a real "adversary," not merely impersonal temptation, help you take the battle seriously? How can you be "sober and vigilant" without being paralyzed by fear, knowing this enemy is defeated by Christ?`,
  },
  {
    day: 8,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "God Tempteth No Man",
    ref: "James 1:13",
    scripture: "Let no man say when he is tempted, I am tempted of God: for God cannot be tempted with evil, neither tempteth he any man.",
    walk: `Friend, this week we turn from understanding temptation to resting in the faithfulness of God, and we begin by clearing away a lie that can poison our whole approach to the battle: the lie that God is the one tempting us. *Let no man say when he is tempted, I am tempted of God: for God cannot be tempted with evil, neither tempteth he any man.* God is not the author of our temptation; He never tempts us to evil. Clearing away this lie is essential, for we cannot trust God in the battle if we secretly believe He is against us in it.

Consider the lie James warns against: *Let no man say when he is tempted, I am tempted of God.* When we are tempted, there can be a subtle tendency to blame God, to feel that He has set us up to fail, that He is the one putting temptation in our path to trip us. This is a poisonous lie, friend, and James warns us firmly against it. We must not say, when we are tempted, that we are tempted of God, for this is simply not true, and believing it would turn our hearts against the very One who is our help in the battle.

And see the reason James gives: *for God cannot be tempted with evil, neither tempteth he any man.* God cannot be tempted with evil; evil has no foothold in His perfectly holy nature. And because He cannot be tempted with evil, neither does He tempt anyone else to evil. It is contrary to His holy character. God is not the author of temptation, not the one luring us toward sin, not the one setting us up to fail. He is holy, and He tempts no one to evil. The temptation comes from our own desires (as we saw last week) and from the enemy, but never from God.

Why is it so important to clear away this lie, friend? Because we cannot trust God in the battle against temptation if we secretly believe He is against us in it. If we think God is the one tempting us, setting us up to fail, then we will not turn to Him for help; we will see Him as part of the problem rather than the source of our deliverance. But once we understand that God tempts no man, that He is not the author of our temptation but our helper against it, we can turn to Him freely, trusting Him as our ally in the battle rather than suspecting Him as its author. Clearing away the lie opens the way to trusting God.

So clear away this lie, friend, and see God rightly as your helper in the battle, not its author. When you are tempted, do not blame God, do not imagine He has set you up to fail, do not turn your heart against Him with the suspicion that He is the one tempting you. God cannot be tempted with evil, and He tempts no one. He is not against you in the battle; He is for you, your faithful helper, your source of strength and deliverance. So turn to Him freely when you are tempted, trusting Him as your ally, knowing that the temptation does not come from Him but that the help against it most certainly does. Clear away the lie, friend, and let the truth of God's holy character open the way to trusting Him fully in the battle against temptation.`,
    prayer: `Lord, clear away from my heart the lie that You are the one tempting me, setting me up to fail. You cannot be tempted with evil, and You tempt no one; it is contrary to Your holy character. Help me to see You rightly, not as the author of my temptation, but as my faithful helper against it. When I am tempted, let me not blame You or turn my heart against You, but turn to You freely, trusting You as my ally in the battle. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, clear away any hidden belief that God is tempting you or setting you up to fail. When tempted, refuse to blame God, and instead turn to Him freely as your faithful helper, trusting Him as your ally in the battle.`,
    reflect: `Have you ever subtly blamed God for your temptation, as though He set you up to fail? How does knowing that "God tempteth no man" free you to turn to Him as your helper rather than suspecting Him as the author of your temptation?`,
  },
  {
    day: 9,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "Able to Succour the Tempted",
    ref: "Hebrews 2:18",
    scripture: "For in that he himself hath suffered being tempted, he is able to succour them that are tempted.",
    walk: `Friend, here is a truth that brings deep comfort and real help in the battle against temptation: our Savior Himself was tempted, and because He was, He is able to help us when we are tempted. *In that he himself hath suffered being tempted, he is able to succour them that are tempted.* Jesus knows the experience of temptation from the inside, having suffered it Himself, and so He is able to come to our aid, to succour us, in our temptation. We do not face temptation with a Savior who does not understand; we face it with One who has been there.

Consider the remarkable truth that *he himself hath suffered being tempted.* Jesus, the Son of God, suffered temptation. He knows what it is to be tempted, to face the pull toward sin, to endure the assault of the tempter. He was tempted in the wilderness, tempted throughout His ministry, tempted in the garden. He suffered temptation, friend, really and truly, experiencing the battle from the inside. This is astonishing and comforting. Our Savior is not distant from our struggle with temptation; He has been in it Himself, suffering being tempted, knowing the experience firsthand.

And see what this qualifies Him to do: *he is able to succour them that are tempted.* Because Jesus Himself suffered being tempted, He is able to succour us, to help us, to come to our aid when we are tempted. The word *succour* means to run to the aid of someone in need, to bring help to one who is struggling. And Jesus is able to do this for us in our temptation, running to our aid, bringing us help, because He Himself knows the experience of temptation and has overcome it. His own experience of temptation qualifies Him to be our helper in ours.

What comfort this brings, friend, in the battle against temptation. We do not face temptation alone, nor do we face it with a Savior who does not understand what we are going through. We face it with One who has suffered temptation Himself, who knows the struggle from the inside, and who is therefore able to come to our aid. When we are tempted, we can turn to Jesus, knowing that He understands, that He has been there, that He is able to help. He is not a distant, uncomprehending Savior, but One who has suffered being tempted and is able to succour us in our temptation.

So turn to Jesus in your temptation, friend, knowing that He understands and is able to help. When you are in the grip of temptation, struggling against its pull, do not imagine that you are alone or that your Savior does not understand. Jesus Himself suffered being tempted; He knows exactly what you are going through; He has been in the battle Himself. And because He has, He is able to succour you, to run to your aid, to bring you the help you need. So cry out to Him in your temptation, friend, and find that you have a Savior who understands your struggle and is able to help you in it. You do not face temptation with a distant Savior, but with One who has suffered being tempted and is able to succour the tempted. So turn to Him, and receive His help.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, what comfort it brings to know that You Yourself suffered being tempted, that You know the experience of temptation from the inside. And because You suffered being tempted, You are able to succour me, to run to my aid, when I am tempted. So when I am in the grip of temptation, help me to turn to You, knowing that You understand my struggle and are able to help me in it. I do not face temptation with a distant Savior, but with One who has been there. Succour me, Lord, in my temptation. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when you are tempted, turn to Jesus as One who understands, having "suffered being tempted" Himself. Cry out to Him for help, knowing He is "able to succour" you, running to your aid in the battle.`,
    reflect: `How does it comfort you to know that Jesus Himself "suffered being tempted" and understands your struggle from the inside? How does His own experience of temptation make Him "able to succour" you when you are tempted?`,
  },
  {
    day: 10,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "Touched with the Feeling of Our Infirmities",
    ref: "Hebrews 4:15",
    scripture: "For we have not an high priest which cannot be touched with the feeling of our infirmities; but was in all points tempted like as we are, yet without sin.",
    walk: `Friend, here the writer of Hebrews deepens the comfort of yesterday, showing us that our great High Priest sympathizes with us in our weakness because He was tempted in all points as we are: *we have not an high priest which cannot be touched with the feeling of our infirmities; but was in all points tempted like as we are, yet without sin.* Jesus, our High Priest, is touched with the feeling of our weaknesses, having been tempted in every way we are, and yet He never sinned. Here is both deep sympathy and perfect victory in our Savior.

Consider what is said of our High Priest: *we have not an high priest which cannot be touched with the feeling of our infirmities.* Jesus, our High Priest, can be touched with the feeling of our infirmities, our weaknesses. He sympathizes with us in our weakness, feeling with us, understanding our frailty, moved by our struggles. This is wonderful, friend. We do not have a cold, distant, unsympathetic High Priest, unmoved by our weakness. We have One who is touched with the feeling of our infirmities, who sympathizes deeply with us in our struggles, who feels with us in our weakness. Our High Priest is full of sympathy for us.

And see the basis of this sympathy: *but was in all points tempted like as we are.* Jesus sympathizes with us because He was tempted in all points, in every way, just as we are. There is no temptation we face that He did not face; He was tempted in all points like as we are. This is why He can sympathize so deeply, friend, because He has experienced the full range of temptation that we experience. He knows the pull of temptation in every area, having been tempted in all points as we are. His sympathy is not theoretical but experiential, rooted in His own full experience of temptation.

And see the crucial difference: *yet without sin.* Though Jesus was tempted in all points as we are, He never sinned. He faced the full force of temptation, in every area, and yet He overcame it completely, without ever sinning. This is enormously important, friend. It means that Jesus not only sympathizes with us in our temptation, but has perfectly overcome temptation Himself. He is not only the sympathetic High Priest who feels our weakness, but the victorious One who faced temptation in all points and never fell. And this victorious, sympathetic High Priest is the One to whom we turn for help in our temptation.

So draw near to your great High Priest in your temptation, friend, finding in Him both deep sympathy and perfect victory. When you struggle with temptation, you do not turn to a cold and distant Savior, but to One who is touched with the feeling of your infirmities, who sympathizes deeply with your weakness, having been tempted in all points just as you are. And you turn to One who not only sympathizes but has perfectly overcome, tempted in all points yet without sin. So bring your weakness and your temptation to this sympathetic, victorious High Priest, and find in Him the help you need, the sympathy that understands and the victory that overcomes. For we have not a High Priest who cannot be touched with the feeling of our infirmities, but One who was tempted in all points like as we are, yet without sin, and who lives to help us in our temptation. So draw near to Him, friend, and find grace to help in your time of need.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, my great High Priest, You are touched with the feeling of my infirmities, sympathizing deeply with my weakness, for You were tempted in all points just as I am. And yet You never sinned, overcoming temptation perfectly. So in my temptation, I draw near to You, finding both deep sympathy and perfect victory. You understand my struggle, and You have overcome. Help me, then, in my time of need, by Your sympathy that understands and Your victory that overcomes. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, draw near to Jesus as your sympathetic High Priest, "touched with the feeling of our infirmities." Bring Him a specific weakness or temptation, finding in Him both the sympathy that understands and the victory that overcomes.`,
    reflect: `How does it help to know your High Priest is "touched with the feeling of your infirmities," sympathizing with your weakness? What does it mean for your battle that Jesus was "tempted in all points" yet overcame "without sin"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 11,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "The Lord Knoweth How to Deliver",
    ref: "2 Peter 2:9",
    scripture: "The Lord knoweth how to deliver the godly out of temptations, and to reserve the unjust unto the day of judgment to be punished.",
    walk: `Friend, here Peter gives us a confident assurance that strengthens us in the battle against temptation: *The Lord knoweth how to deliver the godly out of temptations.* God knows how to deliver us. He is not at a loss, not uncertain, not lacking in ability or wisdom to rescue us from temptation. He knows how to deliver the godly out of temptations, and this confident assurance gives us hope in the midst of the battle. We are not depending on our own ability to deliver ourselves, but on the God who knows how to deliver us.

Consider the confidence of Peter's assurance: *The Lord knoweth how to deliver.* God knows how to deliver us from temptation. This is a statement of God's complete competence and ability in the matter of our deliverance. He is not uncertain about how to rescue us, not lacking in wisdom or power to do it. He knows how. Whatever the temptation, however we may be entangled in it, God knows how to deliver us out of it. This is wonderfully reassuring, friend, for it tells us that our deliverance does not depend on our own cleverness or strength, but on the God who knows exactly how to rescue us.

And see who God delivers: *the godly out of temptations.* God knows how to deliver the godly, those who belong to Him, who walk with Him, out of their temptations. This is a promise for God's people, friend, for those who are seeking to live for Him. God watches over His own, and He knows how to deliver them out of the temptations they face. We who belong to God are not left to fend for ourselves in the battle against temptation; we have a God who knows how to deliver us, and who watches over us to do it.

Notice the contrast Peter draws, which underscores the certainty of God's deliverance: God knows how *to deliver the godly out of temptations, and to reserve the unjust unto the day of judgment.* God's knowledge and ability extend over both the deliverance of His people and the judgment of the wicked. The same God who knows how to reserve the unjust for judgment also knows how to deliver the godly from temptation. His sovereign knowledge and power are at work in both, and this assures us that His ability to deliver us is certain and complete. The God who governs the destiny of all knows perfectly how to deliver His own.

So take confidence in this assurance, friend, in the midst of your battle against temptation. You are not depending on your own ability to deliver yourself, your own cleverness or strength to escape temptation. You are depending on the God who knows how to deliver the godly out of temptations. So when you feel entangled in temptation, unable to see the way out, unsure how you could possibly escape, remember that God knows how to deliver you. He is not at a loss; He knows exactly how to rescue you, even when you cannot see the way. So cry out to Him, trust His ability to deliver, and depend not on your own strength but on the God who knows how to deliver the godly out of temptations. For the Lord knows how to deliver you, friend, and His knowledge and power are equal to your every temptation. Trust the God who knows how to deliver.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for the confident assurance that You know how to deliver the godly out of temptations. You are not at a loss, not uncertain, not lacking the wisdom or power to rescue me. You know how. So when I feel entangled in temptation, unable to see the way out, help me to depend not on my own strength but on Your ability to deliver me. You know how to deliver me, even when I cannot see the way. I trust You, the God who knows how to deliver. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when you feel entangled in temptation and cannot see the way out, rest in the assurance that "the Lord knoweth how to deliver." Depend on His ability to rescue you rather than your own strength, crying out to Him for deliverance.`,
    reflect: `How does it strengthen you to know that "the Lord knoweth how to deliver" you from temptation, even when you cannot see the way out? How does depending on God's ability to deliver differ from depending on your own strength?`,
  },
  {
    day: 12,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "Faithful to Keep You from Evil",
    ref: "2 Thessalonians 3:3",
    scripture: "But the Lord is faithful, who shall stablish you, and keep you from evil.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul gives us a promise that rests entirely on the faithfulness of God: *the Lord is faithful, who shall stablish you, and keep you from evil.* The Lord is faithful, and because He is faithful, He will establish us and keep us from evil. This promise, like our anchor verse, grounds our hope not in our own faithfulness, which fails, but in God's faithfulness, which never fails. In the battle against temptation, this is where our confidence rests: on the faithful God who keeps us.

Consider the foundation of this promise: *the Lord is faithful.* The promise rests on God's faithfulness. This is so important, friend, because our own faithfulness is unreliable. We resolve to do better, and we fail; we promise to resist temptation, and we fall; our faithfulness wavers and breaks. But God's faithfulness never fails. He is faithful, always, unchangingly, reliably. And it is on His faithfulness, not ours, that this promise rests. When we are weak and faltering, when our own faithfulness has failed again, we can still rest on the faithfulness of God, which does not depend on ours and never fails.

And see what the faithful Lord does: *who shall stablish you.* The faithful Lord will establish us, making us firm, steady, settled, strengthening us so that we are not easily shaken or toppled by temptation. To be established is to be made stable, firmly rooted, able to stand. And this is what the faithful Lord does for us, friend. He establishes us, strengthening and steadying us, so that we can stand firm against temptation. We are not left to our own instability, our own weakness and wavering; the faithful Lord establishes us, making us firm and steady in the battle.

And see the second thing the faithful Lord does: *and keep you from evil.* The faithful Lord keeps us from evil, guarding us, protecting us, preserving us from the evil that would overcome us. This is a promise of God's keeping power, friend, His active work to guard and protect us from evil. We are not left to guard ourselves entirely by our own strength; the faithful Lord keeps us, guarding us from the evil that would destroy us. His faithful keeping is at work in our lives, protecting us in the battle against temptation.

So rest your confidence on the faithfulness of God, friend, not on your own. In the battle against temptation, do not place your hope in your own faithfulness, your own resolve, your own ability to resist, for these fail. Place your hope instead on the faithfulness of God, who is faithful when you are faltering, who establishes you when you are unstable, who keeps you from evil when you cannot keep yourself. When you have failed again, when your own faithfulness has broken once more, do not despair, but rest on the faithfulness of God, which does not depend on yours and never fails. For the Lord is faithful, and He will establish you and keep you from evil. So let your confidence rest there, friend, on the faithful God who keeps you, and not on your own unreliable faithfulness. He is faithful, and He will do it.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You are faithful, and because You are faithful, You will establish me and keep me from evil. Help me to rest my confidence on Your faithfulness, not on my own, which fails again and again. When I am weak and faltering, when my own faithfulness has broken once more, remind me that You are faithful still, that You will establish me when I am unstable and keep me from evil when I cannot keep myself. My hope rests on Your faithfulness, Lord, which never fails. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when your own faithfulness fails, rest your confidence on God's faithfulness instead. Trust the "faithful" Lord to "stablish you" and "keep you from evil," placing your hope in His reliability rather than your own.`,
    reflect: `Why is it crucial that this promise rests on the Lord's faithfulness rather than your own? When your own faithfulness fails, how does it help to know that God is "faithful" still, to "stablish you, and keep you from evil"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 13,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "Greater Is He That Is in You",
    ref: "1 John 4:4",
    scripture: "Ye are of God, little children, and have overcome them: because greater is he that is in you, than he that is in the world.",
    walk: `Friend, here John gives us a truth that turns the tide in the battle against temptation, a truth of immense encouragement: *greater is he that is in you, than he that is in the world.* The One who is in us, God Himself by His Spirit, is greater than the enemy who works against us in the world. This means that we fight temptation not from weakness but from a position of strength, for the greater One dwells within us. The power within us is greater than the power against us.

Consider the assurance John gives: *Ye are of God, little children, and have overcome them.* John addresses believers as those who are of God and who *have overcome.* This is remarkable, friend. John speaks of overcoming as something already accomplished, a victory already won. We who are of God have overcome the spirits of error, the forces of the enemy. This is not a victory we are striving toward in our own strength, hoping we might somehow achieve it; it is a victory already won, because of the One who dwells within us. We fight from victory, not merely for it.

And see the reason for this victory: *because greater is he that is in you, than he that is in the world.* The reason we have overcome is that the One who is in us is greater than the one who is in the world. God Himself, by His Spirit, dwells within us, and He is greater, infinitely greater, than the enemy who works against us in the world. This is the great encouragement of this verse, friend. The power within us is greater than the power against us. The One who dwells in us is mightier than all the forces of temptation and the enemy arrayed against us. We are not outmatched in the battle; the greater One is on our side, indeed, within us.

This turns the tide in the battle against temptation, friend. So often we fight temptation feeling outmatched, overpowered, as though the forces against us were greater than any strength we have. And if we were fighting in our own strength, this would be true; we would be outmatched. But we are not fighting in our own strength. The greater One dwells within us, and He is greater than the enemy who works against us. So we fight not from weakness but from strength, not as those who are outmatched but as those in whom the greater power dwells. The tide is turned, for greater is He that is in us than he that is in the world.

So fight temptation from this position of strength, friend, knowing that the One within you is greater than the one against you. When temptation comes and you feel outmatched, overpowered, as though the forces against you were too strong, remember this truth: greater is He that is in you than he that is in the world. You do not fight in your own strength, but in the strength of the greater One who dwells within you. The power within you is greater than the power against you. So do not fight as one who is outmatched and doomed to lose, but as one in whom the greater power dwells, fighting from victory rather than merely for it. For greater is He that is in you, friend, than he that is in the world, and in His strength you can overcome. So draw on the greater One within you, and fight from the strength He provides.`,
    prayer: `Lord, what encouragement to know that greater is He that is in me than he that is in the world. You Yourself, by Your Spirit, dwell within me, and You are greater, infinitely greater, than the enemy who works against me. So when temptation comes and I feel outmatched and overpowered, remind me that the power within me is greater than the power against me. Help me to fight not from weakness but from strength, drawing on the greater One who dwells within me. In Your strength, I can overcome. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, when you feel outmatched by temptation, remember that "greater is he that is in you, than he that is in the world." Fight from this position of strength, drawing on the greater power of God within you rather than your own weakness.`,
    reflect: `How does the truth that "greater is he that is in you, than he that is in the world" change the way you face temptation? What does it mean to fight "from victory" rather than merely "for victory," knowing the greater One dwells within you?`,
  },
  {
    day: 14,
    week: 2,
    weekTitle: "The Faithfulness of God",
    title: "Able to Keep You from Falling",
    ref: "Jude 1:24",
    scripture: "Now unto him that is able to keep you from falling, and to present you faultless before the presence of his glory with exceeding joy.",
    walk: `Friend, we close this week on the faithfulness of God with a doxology of soaring confidence, a verse that lifts our eyes to the God who is able to keep us: *unto him that is able to keep you from falling, and to present you faultless before the presence of his glory with exceeding joy.* God is able to keep us from falling, and He is able to bring us safely home, presenting us faultless before His glory. This is the confident hope on which we rest as we close this week: God is able to keep us, all the way to the end.

Consider the first great assurance: *able to keep you from falling.* God is able to keep us from falling. This is His keeping power, friend, His ability to hold us up, to guard us, to keep us from stumbling and falling in the battle against temptation. We are prone to fall; we have fallen many times; we know our weakness and our tendency to stumble. But God is able to keep us from falling. His power is greater than our weakness, His keeping stronger than our stumbling. We are not left to keep ourselves from falling by our own strength, which fails; we are kept by the God who is able to keep us from falling.

And see the second great assurance: *and to present you faultless before the presence of his glory.* God is able not only to keep us from falling along the way, but to bring us safely home at last, presenting us faultless before the presence of His glory. This is the goal of His keeping, friend, to bring us all the way home, to present us faultless, blameless, before His glorious presence. The God who keeps us from falling is the God who will bring us safely to glory, presenting us faultless at the end. His keeping power extends all the way to the end, ensuring that we will be brought safely home.

And see the joy with which this is done: *with exceeding joy.* God will present us faultless before His glory with exceeding joy. There is joy in this, friend, exceeding joy, abundant joy. The bringing of God's people safely home, presented faultless before His glory, is an occasion of exceeding joy, both His joy and ours. This is where the keeping power of God is leading, to a destination of exceeding joy, when we are presented faultless before His glorious presence. The battle against temptation is not endless and joyless; it is leading toward this glorious, joyful end.

So rest in this confident hope as you close the week, friend: God is able to keep you from falling and to bring you safely home. In the battle against temptation, you are not depending on your own ability to keep yourself from falling, which fails; you are kept by the God who is able to keep you from falling, and who will bring you safely all the way home, presenting you faultless before His glory with exceeding joy. So do not despair when you feel weak and prone to fall, for you are kept not by your own strength but by the God who is able to keep you. And do not lose heart in the long battle, for it is leading toward a glorious, joyful end, when you will be presented faultless before His presence with exceeding joy. So rest in the God who is able, friend, to keep you from falling and to bring you safely home. He is able, and He will do it.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You are able to keep me from falling, and to present me faultless before the presence of Your glory with exceeding joy. When I feel weak and prone to fall, remind me that I am kept not by my own strength, which fails, but by Your keeping power, which is able to hold me up. And when I grow weary in the long battle, lift my eyes to the joyful end toward which it leads, when You will present me faultless before Your glory with exceeding joy. I rest in You, the God who is able to keep me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, rest in the confident hope that God is "able to keep you from falling" and to bring you safely home. When you feel weak and prone to stumble, depend on His keeping power rather than your own strength.`,
    reflect: `How does it strengthen you to know God is "able to keep you from falling," even though you are weak and prone to stumble? How does lifting your eyes to the joyful end, being "presented faultless before His glory," encourage you in the long battle?`,
  },
  {
    day: 15,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "It Is Written",
    ref: "Matthew 4:4",
    scripture: "But he answered and said, It is written, Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceedeth out of the mouth of God.",
    walk: `Friend, this week we take up the weapons of victory God has given us, and we begin with the weapon Jesus Himself wielded against the tempter: the Word of God. When tempted in the wilderness, Jesus answered each temptation with Scripture: *It is written.* He met the tempter not with His own arguments or willpower, but with the written Word of God. And in doing so, He showed us the first and foremost weapon in the battle against temptation: the Word of God, wielded against the tempter.

Consider the situation. Jesus, having fasted forty days in the wilderness, was tempted by the devil. And how did Jesus respond to each temptation? Not with His own reasoning, not with sheer willpower, not with clever arguments, but with Scripture: *It is written.* Three times the tempter came, and three times Jesus answered, *It is written,* wielding the written Word of God against each temptation. This is deeply instructive, friend. If Jesus, the sinless Son of God, met temptation with the written Word, how much more must we take up this same weapon in our own battles?

See how Jesus used the Word: *It is written, Man shall not live by bread alone, but by every word that proceedeth out of the mouth of God.* The tempter had urged Jesus to turn stones into bread, to satisfy His hunger in a way outside the Father's will. And Jesus answered with a specific word of Scripture that addressed the specific temptation, declaring that man lives not by bread alone but by every word of God. He met the particular temptation with a particular truth from God's Word, wielding the Scripture precisely against the lie of the temptation. This is how the Word is used as a weapon, friend: specific truth applied against specific temptation.

This shows us that the Word of God is our first and foremost weapon against temptation, friend. When temptation comes, often wrapped in lies and false promises, the Word of God speaks the truth that exposes and counters those lies. The tempter says, *this will satisfy you, this is good for you, God is withholding something good from you;* and the Word of God answers with the truth that counters these lies. The Word is the sword of the Spirit, the weapon that cuts through the deceptions of temptation with the truth of God. And it is a weapon we must learn to wield, as Jesus did, answering temptation with *It is written.*

So take up the Word of God as your weapon against temptation, friend, as Jesus did in the wilderness. When temptation comes, do not try to fight it merely with your own willpower or reasoning, but answer it with the truth of God's Word, *It is written.* Learn the Scriptures that counter the particular temptations you face, so that when the tempter comes with his lies, you can answer with the truth, wielding the Word against him as Jesus did. This is the first and foremost weapon in the battle, friend, the sword of the Spirit, which is the Word of God. So learn to wield it, answering every temptation with *It is written,* and meeting the lies of the tempter with the truth of God. For if Jesus overcame temptation with the written Word, so may you, in His strength, take up the same mighty weapon.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, when You were tempted in the wilderness, You met the tempter not with Your own willpower but with the written Word of God: "It is written." Teach me to wield this same weapon in my battles against temptation. Help me to learn the Scriptures that counter the temptations I face, so that when the tempter comes with his lies, I can answer with Your truth. Make the Word of God my first and foremost weapon, the sword of the Spirit, with which I overcome temptation as You did. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take up the Word of God as your weapon, as Jesus did. Identify one specific Scripture that counters a temptation you face, and be ready to answer that temptation with "It is written," wielding the truth against the lie.`,
    reflect: `How did Jesus model using the Word of God as a weapon against temptation in the wilderness? What specific Scriptures might you learn to counter the particular temptations you face, answering them with "It is written"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 16,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "Thy Word Have I Hid in Mine Heart",
    ref: "Psalm 119:11",
    scripture: "Thy word have I hid in mine heart, that I might not sin against thee.",
    walk: `Friend, having seen that the Word of God is our weapon against temptation, today we learn how to have that weapon ready when we need it: *Thy word have I hid in mine heart, that I might not sin against thee.* The psalmist hid God's Word in his heart, storing it up within him, precisely so that he might not sin. This is how we keep the weapon of the Word ready for the battle, friend: by hiding it in our hearts ahead of time, so that it is there when temptation comes.

Consider what the psalmist did: *Thy word have I hid in mine heart.* He hid God's Word in his heart, treasuring it up within him, storing it deep inside. To hide the Word in the heart is to take it in, to memorize it, to meditate on it, to let it dwell richly within us, so that it becomes part of us, stored up and ready. This is more than occasional reading; it is the deliberate storing up of God's Word within the heart, so that it is there, ready, when we need it. The psalmist had hidden God's Word in his heart, treasuring it up within him.

And see his purpose: *that I might not sin against thee.* The psalmist hid God's Word in his heart precisely so that he might not sin. He understood the connection between having God's Word stored in his heart and being kept from sin. The hidden Word guards the heart against sin, friend. When God's Word is stored up within us, it is there to counsel us, to warn us, to strengthen us, to counter temptation in the moment it comes. The psalmist hid the Word in his heart as a guard against sin, knowing that the stored-up Word would help keep him from sinning.

This shows us how to keep the weapon of the Word ready for the battle, friend. Yesterday we saw that the Word is our weapon against temptation. But a weapon is only useful if it is ready when we need it. And the way to have the Word ready is to hide it in our hearts ahead of time, before the temptation comes. If we wait until temptation strikes to go searching for the right Scripture, we may not find it in time. But if we have hidden God's Word in our hearts beforehand, it is there, ready, rising up to counter the temptation in the moment it comes. The hidden Word is the ready weapon.

So hide God's Word in your heart, friend, that you might have the weapon ready when temptation comes. Do not wait until the moment of temptation to go searching for the truth you need; store up God's Word within your heart ahead of time, memorizing it, meditating on it, treasuring it up within you, so that it is there, ready, when the battle comes. Hide in your heart the specific Scriptures that counter the temptations you face, so that they rise up within you in the moment of need, guarding you against sin. For the psalmist hid God's Word in his heart that he might not sin, and so may you. The hidden Word is the ready weapon, friend, and the heart stored with Scripture is the heart prepared for the battle. So hide God's Word in your heart, that you might not sin against Him, and that you might have the sword of the Spirit ready when the tempter comes.`,
    prayer: `Lord, the psalmist hid Your Word in his heart that he might not sin against You, and I want to do the same. Help me to store up Your Word within me ahead of time, memorizing it, meditating on it, treasuring it up within my heart, so that it is there, ready, when temptation comes. Let the hidden Word guard me against sin, rising up within me to counter the tempter in the moment of need. Make my heart a storehouse of Your Word, prepared for the battle. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, begin hiding God's Word in your heart so the weapon is ready before temptation comes. Memorize one Scripture that counters a temptation you face, storing it up within you so it rises up in the moment of need.`,
    reflect: `Why is it important to hide God's Word in your heart "ahead of time," before temptation comes, rather than searching for it in the moment? What specific Scriptures might you store up to guard you against the temptations you face?`,
  },
  {
    day: 17,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "Resist the Devil",
    ref: "James 4:7",
    scripture: "Submit yourselves therefore to God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you.",
    walk: `Friend, here James gives us a two-part strategy for victory that pairs submission to God with resistance to the devil, and attaches a wonderful promise: *Submit yourselves therefore to God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you.* When we submit to God and resist the devil, the devil flees from us. This is an active weapon in the battle against temptation, friend, resistance grounded in submission to God, and it comes with the promise that the enemy will flee.

Consider the first part of the strategy: *Submit yourselves therefore to God.* Before we resist the devil, we submit to God. This order is important, friend. Our resistance to the devil is grounded in our submission to God; we resist the enemy from a position of yieldedness to God, under His authority, in His strength. We cannot effectively resist the devil while in rebellion against God; the resistance flows from submission. So the first step is to submit ourselves to God, yielding to His authority, placing ourselves under His lordship, drawing on His strength. From this position of submission, we are able to resist the devil.

And see the second part: *Resist the devil.* Grounded in submission to God, we are to resist the devil, actively standing against him, refusing to yield to his temptations, opposing him in the strength God provides. This is active, friend. We are not merely to passively endure the devil's assaults, but to actively resist him, standing firm against his temptations, refusing to give in. Resistance is an active weapon in the battle, a deliberate standing against the enemy, a refusal to yield. We submit to God, and from that position, we actively resist the devil.

And see the wonderful promise attached: *and he will flee from you.* When we submit to God and resist the devil, the devil flees from us. This is a remarkable promise, friend. The roaring lion we met last week, the adversary who prowls about seeking to devour us, flees when we resist him in submission to God. He is not as invincible as he appears; when met with resistance grounded in submission to God, he flees. This tells us that the enemy can be made to flee, that our resistance, in God's strength, is effective, that the devil is a defeated foe who flees before the resisting, submitted believer.

So take up this active weapon of resistance, friend, grounded in submission to God. Do not merely passively endure the devil's temptations; actively resist him, standing firm against him, refusing to yield. But ground your resistance in submission to God, yielding to His authority, drawing on His strength, for it is from this position of submission that effective resistance flows. And take hold of the promise: when you submit to God and resist the devil, he will flee from you. The enemy is not invincible; he flees before the resisting, submitted believer. So submit yourself to God, friend, and resist the devil, and watch him flee. You are not helpless before the enemy; in submission to God, you can actively resist him, and he will flee from you. So take up this weapon of resistance, grounded in submission, and stand firm against the enemy, who will flee before you in the strength God provides.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me to submit myself to You and resist the devil, with the promise that he will flee from me. Help me first to submit myself fully to You, yielding to Your authority, placing myself under Your lordship, drawing on Your strength. And from that position of submission, help me to actively resist the devil, standing firm against his temptations, refusing to yield. Thank You for the promise that when I resist him in submission to You, he will flee. Give me the strength to resist, and make the enemy flee before me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take up the weapon of resistance grounded in submission. First submit yourself to God, yielding to His authority; then actively resist the devil, standing firm against a temptation, trusting the promise that "he will flee from you."`,
    reflect: `Why must resistance to the devil be grounded in submission to God first? How does the promise "resist the devil, and he will flee from you" change your view of the enemy's power, and embolden you to actively resist temptation?`,
  },
  {
    day: 18,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "Flee Youthful Lusts",
    ref: "2 Timothy 2:22",
    scripture: "Flee also youthful lusts: but follow righteousness, faith, charity, peace, with them that call on the Lord out of a pure heart.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul gives us a weapon that may at first seem like weakness but is in fact great wisdom: fleeing. *Flee also youthful lusts: but follow righteousness, faith, charity, peace.* Sometimes the path to victory over temptation is not to stand and fight, but to flee, to run away from the temptation, to remove ourselves from its presence. And Paul pairs this fleeing with pursuing, fleeing from lust and following after righteousness. This is wisdom for the battle, knowing when to flee and what to pursue.

Consider the command: *Flee also youthful lusts.* Paul tells Timothy to flee youthful lusts, the strong desires and passions that tempt the young especially, but that tempt us all. Notice that Paul does not say to stand and fight these lusts, to reason with them, to see how close we can get to them without falling. He says to flee them, to run away, to remove ourselves from their presence. This is important wisdom, friend. There are some temptations that we are not to stand and fight, but to flee. To linger near them, to flirt with them, to test our strength against them, is folly; the wise course is to flee.

This may seem like weakness, friend, but it is in fact great wisdom and strength. We sometimes think that the brave, strong thing is to stand and face temptation, to prove that we can resist it without fleeing. But this is often pride and folly, not strength. The truly wise and strong course, with certain temptations, is to flee, to remove ourselves from the temptation's presence, to refuse to linger where we are vulnerable. Joseph fled from Potiphar's wife; he did not stand and reason with the temptation, but fled. Fleeing is not cowardice, friend; it is wisdom, the recognition that some temptations are best overcome not by standing and fighting but by removing ourselves from their presence.

And see what Paul pairs with fleeing: *but follow righteousness, faith, charity, peace.* We are not only to flee from lust, but to follow after righteousness, faith, love, and peace. Fleeing and following go together, friend. We flee from the temptation, and we pursue the good, running away from what is evil and running toward what is good. This is wise, for it is not enough merely to flee from temptation; we must also fill the void with the pursuit of good. As we flee youthful lusts, we follow after righteousness, faith, charity, and peace, replacing the pursuit of evil with the pursuit of good.

So learn the wisdom of fleeing, friend, and pair it with the pursuit of good. Recognize that with certain temptations, the path to victory is not to stand and fight, to linger near the temptation testing your strength, but to flee, to remove yourself from its presence. This is not weakness but wisdom, the wisdom that knows some temptations are best overcome by fleeing. So when you face such temptations, do not linger, do not flirt with them, do not test your strength against them, but flee, removing yourself from their presence. And as you flee from evil, follow after good, pursuing righteousness, faith, love, and peace, filling the void with the pursuit of what is good. For the wise know when to flee and what to pursue, friend, fleeing youthful lusts and following after righteousness. So take up this weapon of fleeing, paired with the pursuit of good, and find in it not weakness but the wisdom of victory.`,
    prayer: `Lord, teach me the wisdom of fleeing. Help me to recognize that with certain temptations, the path to victory is not to stand and fight, lingering near the temptation to test my strength, but to flee, removing myself from its presence. Keep me from the pride and folly that thinks fleeing is weakness, and give me the wisdom to flee when I should. And as I flee from evil, help me to follow after righteousness, faith, love, and peace, filling the void with the pursuit of what is good. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, identify a temptation that you should flee rather than fight, and remove yourself from its presence. Then pair the fleeing with pursuing: follow after righteousness, faith, love, or peace, filling the void with good.`,
    reflect: `Why is fleeing certain temptations a mark of wisdom rather than weakness? What temptation might you need to flee, removing yourself from its presence, and what good might you "follow" after to fill the void?`,
  },
  {
    day: 19,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "Flee Fornication",
    ref: "1 Corinthians 6:18",
    scripture: "Flee fornication. Every sin that a man doeth is without the body; but he that committeth fornication sinneth against his own body.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul applies the wisdom of fleeing to a specific and powerful area of temptation, sexual sin: *Flee fornication.* This is one area where Paul is especially emphatic that we are to flee, not to stand and fight. Sexual temptation is powerful, and the wise course is not to linger near it, testing our strength, but to flee from it. Paul's directness here is a mercy to us, giving us clear wisdom for one of the most common and powerful areas of temptation.

Consider Paul's direct command: *Flee fornication.* Paul does not mince words. He does not say to carefully manage sexual temptation, to see how close we can get without falling, to stand and reason with it. He says, simply and directly, *flee.* Run from it. Remove yourself from its presence. This directness is a mercy, friend, for sexual temptation is one of the most powerful temptations we face, and the clear command to flee gives us the wisdom we need. With this temptation especially, the path to victory is to flee, not to linger and fight.

Why is fleeing so especially important with this temptation, friend? Because sexual temptation has a peculiar power to overcome our reason and resolve when we linger near it. Many who were sure they could resist have fallen because they lingered too close, flirted with the temptation, tested their strength against it. The power of this temptation is such that lingering near it is exceedingly dangerous. And so Paul's command is to flee, to remove ourselves from the situations, the images, the relationships, the circumstances that tempt us in this way, rather than lingering near them and trusting in our own strength to resist.

And see the reason Paul gives for the seriousness of this sin: *he that committeth fornication sinneth against his own body.* Paul notes that sexual sin has a peculiar character, that it is a sin against one's own body. He is underscoring the seriousness and the peculiar nature of this sin, which is why he is so emphatic that we flee it. Sexual sin is not a light thing; it has profound effects, sinning against one's own body in a way other sins do not. And this seriousness underscores Paul's command to flee, to take this temptation with the utmost seriousness and to remove ourselves from its presence rather than lingering near it.

So take Paul's direct command to heart, friend, and flee sexual temptation rather than lingering near it. With this powerful temptation especially, do not test your strength, do not see how close you can get, do not linger near the images and situations and relationships that tempt you. Flee. Remove yourself from the temptation's presence. This is not weakness but wisdom, the wisdom that recognizes the peculiar power of this temptation and the danger of lingering near it. And if you have fallen in this area, friend, do not despair, for the grace and forgiveness we explored in earlier books is fully available to you; there is full cleansing and a fresh start in Christ. But going forward, take up the wisdom of fleeing, removing yourself from the temptation's presence rather than trusting your own strength near it. For Paul's command is clear and merciful: flee fornication. So flee, friend, in the strength God provides, and find in fleeing the path of victory over this powerful temptation.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You give me the clear and merciful command to flee sexual temptation, not to linger near it testing my strength. Help me to take this command to heart, recognizing the peculiar power of this temptation and the danger of lingering near it. Give me the wisdom and resolve to flee, to remove myself from the situations, images, and relationships that tempt me in this way. And where I have fallen, thank You for Your full forgiveness and fresh start in Christ. Going forward, help me to flee, in the strength You provide. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take Paul's direct command seriously: flee, rather than linger near, sexual temptation. Identify the situations, images, or relationships that tempt you in this area, and take a concrete step to remove yourself from their presence.`,
    reflect: `Why is "flee" the wise command for sexual temptation especially, rather than lingering near it to test your strength? What concrete steps might you take to "flee," removing yourself from situations where this temptation has power?`,
  },
  {
    day: 20,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "Make No Provision for the Flesh",
    ref: "Romans 13:14",
    scripture: "But put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ, and make not provision for the flesh, to fulfil the lusts thereof.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul gives us a weapon of great practical wisdom, one that strikes at temptation before it even begins: *make not provision for the flesh, to fulfil the lusts thereof.* To make provision for the flesh is to make arrangements, to provide opportunity, to set ourselves up for the fulfilling of sinful desires. And Paul tells us not to do this, to cut off the provisions, to refuse to set ourselves up to sin. Paired with putting on Christ, this is wisdom that addresses temptation at its root.

Consider the negative command: *make not provision for the flesh, to fulfil the lusts thereof.* To make provision for the flesh is to make arrangements that provide opportunity for sin, to set things up so that the fulfilling of sinful desire becomes easy and likely. Paul tells us not to do this, not to make such provision, not to arrange our lives in ways that provide opportunity for the flesh to fulfill its lusts. This is profoundly practical wisdom, friend. So often we fall into temptation because we have, knowingly or unknowingly, made provision for it, arranging our lives in ways that provide easy opportunity for sin. Paul tells us to cut off these provisions, to refuse to set ourselves up to sin.

This strikes at temptation before it even begins, friend. Rather than waiting to fight temptation in the heat of the moment, when desire is strong and resistance is hard, we cut off the provisions ahead of time, removing the opportunities and arrangements that make sin easy. If we know that certain situations, certain access, certain arrangements provide opportunity for our particular temptations, the wise course is to cut off those provisions ahead of time, so that the temptation has no easy opportunity. We make no provision for the flesh, removing the arrangements that would fulfill its lusts before the temptation even arises.

And see what Paul pairs with this: *put ye on the Lord Jesus Christ.* Alongside making no provision for the flesh, we are to put on the Lord Jesus Christ, clothing ourselves with Him, taking on His character, walking in His strength. This positive action accompanies the negative one, friend. We cut off provision for the flesh, and we put on Christ, removing the opportunities for sin while clothing ourselves with the Savior. The two go together: putting off the provisions for sin and putting on Christ. We do not merely create a void by cutting off provisions; we fill our lives with Christ, putting Him on, walking in His strength and character.

So take up this practical weapon, friend, of making no provision for the flesh while putting on Christ. Look honestly at your life and ask where you have been making provision for the flesh, arranging things in ways that provide easy opportunity for your particular temptations. And then cut off those provisions, removing the arrangements and opportunities that make sin easy, striking at temptation before it even begins. Do not wait to fight temptation in the heat of the moment; cut off its provisions ahead of time. And as you do, put on the Lord Jesus Christ, clothing yourself with Him, filling your life with His presence and strength and character. For this is great practical wisdom in the battle against temptation, friend: to make no provision for the flesh, removing the opportunities for sin, while putting on Christ, filling your life with the Savior. So cut off the provisions, put on Christ, and strike at temptation before it even begins.`,
    prayer: `Lord, give me the practical wisdom to make no provision for the flesh, to fulfil its lusts. Show me where I have been arranging my life in ways that provide easy opportunity for my temptations, and help me to cut off those provisions ahead of time, striking at temptation before it even begins. And help me to put on the Lord Jesus Christ, clothing myself with You, filling my life with Your presence, strength, and character. Let me put off the provisions for sin and put on the Savior. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, identify one way you have been "making provision for the flesh", arranging things that provide easy opportunity for temptation, and cut it off ahead of time. Then "put on" Christ, filling that space with His presence and strength.`,
    reflect: `Where have you been "making provision for the flesh," setting yourself up for temptation without realizing it? How does cutting off these provisions ahead of time strike at temptation "before it even begins," and what would it mean to "put on Christ" in their place?`,
  },
  {
    day: 21,
    week: 3,
    weekTitle: "The Weapons of Victory",
    title: "The Whole Armour of God",
    ref: "Ephesians 6:13",
    scripture: "Wherefore take unto you the whole armour of God, that ye may be able to withstand in the evil day, and having done all, to stand.",
    walk: `Friend, we close this week on the weapons of victory with Paul's call to take up the whole armour of God: *take unto you the whole armour of God, that ye may be able to withstand in the evil day, and having done all, to stand.* God has provided a complete armour for the spiritual battle, and we are to take up the whole of it, that we might be able to stand firm against the assaults of the enemy. This gathers up all the weapons we have explored and reminds us that our defense is found in the armour God provides.

Consider the call: *take unto you the whole armour of God.* We are to take up the armour, the complete armour, that God has provided. Notice that it is the armour *of God*, provided by Him, not manufactured by us. And notice that we are to take up the *whole* armour, not just part of it, not picking and choosing, but taking up the complete protection God has provided. This is important, friend. Our defense in the spiritual battle is found in the armour God provides, and we are to take up the whole of it, leaving no part of ourselves unprotected. The complete armour of God is our defense against the complete assault of the enemy.

And see the purpose: *that ye may be able to withstand in the evil day.* The armour is given that we may be able to withstand, to stand firm, in the evil day, the day of intense spiritual assault and temptation. There are evil days, friend, days when the assault of temptation and the enemy is especially intense. And the whole armour of God is given precisely so that we may be able to withstand in such days, to stand firm when the assault is fiercest. We take up the armour so that we will be able to stand in the evil day, not collapsing under the assault, but withstanding it in the protection God provides.

And see the goal, repeated for emphasis: *and having done all, to stand.* The goal of taking up the armour is to stand, to remain standing, to hold our ground against the enemy. Notice that the goal is not necessarily to advance and conquer in some dramatic way, but simply to stand, to hold our ground, to remain standing when the battle is over. This is itself a great victory in the spiritual battle, friend, to stand firm, to hold our ground, to still be standing when the assault has passed. And the whole armour of God enables us to do this, to stand, having done all, in the strength God provides.

So take up the whole armour of God, friend, that you may stand firm in the battle against temptation. All the weapons we have explored this week, the Word, prayer, resistance, fleeing, making no provision for the flesh, are part of the equipment God provides for the battle. And Paul calls us to take up the whole of God's armour, leaving no part of ourselves unprotected, so that we may be able to withstand in the evil day and, having done all, to stand. Our defense is not found in our own strength or resources, but in the armour God provides. So take it up, friend, the whole of it, and stand firm in the strength of God, able to withstand the assaults of the enemy in the evil day. For God has provided a complete armour for the battle, and clothed in it, you are able to stand. So take up the whole armour of God, and having done all, stand.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You have provided a complete armour for the spiritual battle, and You call me to take up the whole of it, that I might be able to stand firm against the assaults of the enemy. Help me to take up the whole armour of God, leaving no part of myself unprotected, so that I may withstand in the evil day and, having done all, stand. Let my defense be found not in my own strength, but in the armour You provide. Clothe me in Your armour, Lord, that I might stand firm in the battle. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take up "the whole armour of God," leaving no part of yourself unprotected. Consider the weapons you have explored this week, and make sure you are taking up the complete protection God provides, that you may "stand" firm in the battle.`,
    reflect: `Why are we to take up the "whole" armour of God, not just part of it? How does it encourage you that the goal is simply "to stand", to hold your ground in the evil day, in the strength of the armour God provides?`,
  },
  {
    day: 22,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Get Thee Hence, Satan",
    ref: "Matthew 4:10",
    scripture: "Then saith Jesus unto him, Get thee hence, Satan: for it is written, Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God, and him only shalt thou serve.",
    walk: `Friend, this final week we fix our eyes on victory through Christ, and we begin where the wilderness temptation ended, with Jesus' decisive triumph over the tempter: *Get thee hence, Satan.* After resisting each temptation with the Word, Jesus finally dismissed the tempter with authority, and the devil departed. Here is Christ our victor, who has overcome the very tempter who assaults us, and whose victory becomes the ground of our own.

Consider the authority with which Jesus dismissed the tempter: *Get thee hence, Satan.* After three temptations, each met with *It is written,* Jesus finally commanded the tempter to depart, dismissing him with divine authority. There is power in these words, friend. Jesus did not negotiate with the tempter, did not linger in the struggle, but commanded him to depart, *Get thee hence, Satan.* And Scripture tells us that the devil then left Him. Jesus had triumphed over the tempter, decisively dismissing him with authority. Here is Christ our victor, overcoming the tempter in the wilderness.

And see the truth on which Jesus stood: *for it is written, Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God, and him only shalt thou serve.* Even in dismissing the tempter, Jesus stood on the Word, declaring that God alone is to be worshiped and served. The tempter had offered Jesus the kingdoms of the world in exchange for worship, and Jesus answered with the truth that God alone is to be worshiped. His victory was grounded in unwavering devotion to God, refusing to give to the tempter what belongs to God alone. This is the heart of His triumph: an absolute devotion to God that the tempter could not overcome.

Now why does this matter so deeply for us, friend? Because Christ's victory over the tempter becomes the ground of our own victory. Jesus did not overcome the tempter merely as an example for us to imitate in our own strength, though He is that. He overcame as our representative, our champion, defeating the very enemy who assaults us, and His victory is now ours through faith in Him. When we face the tempter, we do not face an undefeated foe; we face an enemy already conquered by our victorious Christ. And we fight not to achieve a victory not yet won, but from the victory Christ has already won over the tempter.

So fix your eyes on Christ your victor, friend, who has overcome the very tempter who assaults you. When the tempter comes against you, remember that he is a defeated foe, conquered by Christ in the wilderness and finally at the cross. And take heart that Christ's victory becomes the ground of your own; you fight not as one hoping to achieve victory in your own strength, but as one united to the victorious Christ, who has already overcome the tempter. So you too can say, in His authority and strength, *Get thee hence, Satan,* standing on the Word as He did, devoted to God alone, dismissing the defeated tempter in the power of your victorious Lord. For Christ has overcome the tempter, friend, and His victory is yours. So fight from His victory, and watch the defeated enemy flee before the authority of your conquering Christ.`,
    prayer: `Lord Jesus, You overcame the tempter in the wilderness, dismissing him with authority: "Get thee hence, Satan." You stood on the Word, devoted to God alone, and the tempter departed. Thank You that Your victory over the tempter becomes the ground of my own. When the enemy comes against me, help me to remember that he is a defeated foe, conquered by You. Let me fight not to achieve a victory not yet won, but from the victory You have already won. In Your authority and strength, I dismiss the defeated tempter. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, fix your eyes on Christ your victor, who has already overcome the tempter. When temptation comes, face it not as an undefeated foe but as an enemy already conquered by Christ, fighting from His victory rather than for a victory not yet won.`,
    reflect: `How does it change your battle to know that Christ has already overcome the very tempter who assaults you? What does it mean to fight "from" Christ's victory rather than striving to achieve victory in your own strength?`,
  },
  {
    day: 23,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Let Not Sin Reign",
    ref: "Romans 6:12",
    scripture: "Let not sin therefore reign in your mortal body, that ye should obey it in the lusts thereof.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul issues a command that assumes a wonderful truth: that sin no longer has to reign over us. *Let not sin therefore reign in your mortal body, that ye should obey it in the lusts thereof.* Sin once reigned over us as a king, ruling us, commanding our obedience. But Paul commands us not to let sin reign, which assumes that, through Christ, sin's reign has been broken and we no longer have to obey it. This is the foundation of victory: sin is a dethroned king, and we need not obey it.

Consider the command: *Let not sin therefore reign in your mortal body.* Paul commands us not to let sin reign over us. Now this command assumes something wonderful, friend. If Paul commands us not to let sin reign, it must be that we no longer have to let it reign, that sin's reign over us has been broken, that we now have the power to refuse its rule. Paul would not command us not to let sin reign if we were still helpless under its dominion. The very command assumes that, through Christ, sin's reign has been broken, and we now have the ability to refuse to let it rule us.

Consider what it means that sin once *reigned.* Sin reigned over us as a king, ruling our lives, commanding our obedience, exercising dominion over us. We were under its dominion, its slaves, helpless to resist its rule. This was our condition apart from Christ, friend, under the reign of sin, obeying its commands, ruled by its lusts. But the gospel declares that, through Christ, sin's reign has been broken. We have been freed from sin's dominion, delivered from its rule, so that it no longer reigns over us as it once did. Sin is now a dethroned king.

And see what this means for the battle: *that ye should obey it in the lusts thereof.* Because sin's reign has been broken, we no longer have to obey it in its lusts. We are no longer its helpless slaves, bound to obey its every command. We can now refuse to obey sin, refuse to let it reign, refuse to carry out its lusts, for its dominion over us has been broken by Christ. This is the foundation of victory over temptation, friend. We do not fight sin as helpless slaves still under its reign, but as those who have been freed from its dominion, who can now refuse to let it reign, who no longer have to obey it.

So live in light of this wonderful truth, friend: sin is a dethroned king, and you no longer have to obey it. When temptation comes, urging you to obey sin's lusts, remember that you are not sin's helpless slave, bound to obey. Through Christ, sin's reign over you has been broken; it is a dethroned king, and you can refuse to let it reign. So do not let sin reign in your body, do not obey it in its lusts, do not submit to the rule of a king who has been dethroned. You have been freed from sin's dominion by Christ, and you now have the power to refuse its rule. So exercise that power, friend, refusing to let the dethroned king reign, refusing to obey the sin whose dominion has been broken. For sin no longer has to reign over you; through Christ, you are free to refuse its rule. So let not sin reign, friend, for you are no longer its slave, but free in Christ.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that through Christ, sin's reign over me has been broken, so that it is now a dethroned king. Your command not to let sin reign assumes that I no longer have to let it rule me. Help me to live in light of this truth. When temptation comes, urging me to obey sin's lusts, remind me that I am not its helpless slave, but free in Christ to refuse its rule. Help me not to let the dethroned king reign, but to walk in the freedom You have won for me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, live in light of the truth that sin is a "dethroned king" you no longer have to obey. When temptation urges you to obey sin's lusts, refuse to let the dethroned king reign, exercising the freedom Christ has won for you.`,
    reflect: `How does the command "let not sin reign" assume that sin's reign over you has been broken? What does it mean to live as one freed from sin's dominion, refusing to obey a "dethroned king"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 24,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Dead Indeed unto Sin",
    ref: "Romans 6:11",
    scripture: "Likewise reckon ye also yourselves to be dead indeed unto sin, but alive unto God through Jesus Christ our Lord.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul gives us a key to victory over temptation that lies in how we reckon, how we count, our own identity: *reckon ye also yourselves to be dead indeed unto sin, but alive unto God through Jesus Christ our Lord.* Through our union with Christ in His death and resurrection, we have died to sin and are alive to God. And Paul calls us to reckon this true, to count on it, to live in light of this new identity. This reckoning is a powerful key to victory.

Consider the new reality Paul describes: *dead indeed unto sin, but alive unto God through Jesus Christ.* Through our union with Christ, we have died to sin and become alive to God. When Christ died, we died with Him, dying to sin; when Christ rose, we rose with Him, alive to God. This is our new identity, friend, our new reality in Christ: dead to sin, alive to God. We are no longer who we were, bound to sin and dead to God; through Christ, we have died to sin and become alive to God. This is the foundational truth of our new identity in Christ.

And see what Paul calls us to do with this truth: *reckon ye also yourselves to be dead indeed unto sin.* Paul calls us to *reckon* this true, to count it, to consider it so, to act on the basis of it. The word *reckon* is an accounting term, meaning to count something as true and to act accordingly. We are to reckon ourselves dead to sin and alive to God, counting this new identity as true, and living in light of it. This is a powerful key to victory, friend, for how we reckon our identity shapes how we live. When we reckon ourselves dead to sin and alive to God, we live in light of that reality, and it transforms our response to temptation.

Consider how this reckoning works in the battle against temptation, friend. When temptation comes, it appeals to us as though we were still who we used to be, still bound to sin, still its slaves. But we are to reckon ourselves dead to sin, counting it true that, through Christ, we have died to sin and are no longer its slaves. And when we reckon this true, when we count on our new identity, we are able to respond to temptation as those who have died to sin, refusing to live as though we were still its slaves. The reckoning shapes the response. We reckon ourselves dead to sin, and so we refuse to live in it.

So reckon yourself dead to sin and alive to God, friend, and let this reckoning be a key to your victory. When temptation comes, appealing to you as though you were still bound to sin, reckon the truth: through Christ, you have died to sin and become alive to God. Count this true, consider it so, act on the basis of it. You are not who you used to be, not sin's slave, not bound to its rule; you have died to sin and are alive to God through Jesus Christ. So live in light of this new identity, reckoning yourself dead to sin and alive to God, and let this reckoning shape your response to temptation. For how you reckon your identity shapes how you live, friend, and when you reckon yourself dead to sin and alive to God, you are able to refuse temptation as one who belongs no longer to sin but to God. So reckon it true, and live in the power of your new identity in Christ.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that through my union with Christ in His death and resurrection, I have died to sin and become alive to God. Help me to reckon this true, to count on my new identity, to live in light of it. When temptation comes, appealing to me as though I were still bound to sin, help me to reckon myself dead to sin and alive to God through Jesus Christ. Let this reckoning shape my response to temptation, that I might refuse it as one who belongs no longer to sin, but to You. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, "reckon" yourself "dead indeed unto sin, but alive unto God." When temptation appeals to you as though you were still sin's slave, count on your new identity in Christ, and let that reckoning shape how you respond.`,
    reflect: `What does it mean to "reckon" yourself dead to sin and alive to God, counting your new identity as true? How does the way you reckon your identity in Christ shape your response when temptation comes?`,
  },
  {
    day: 25,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Yield Yourselves unto God",
    ref: "Romans 6:13",
    scripture: "Neither yield ye your members as instruments of unrighteousness unto sin: but yield yourselves unto God, as those that are alive from the dead, and your members as instruments of righteousness unto God.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul moves from reckoning to yielding, showing us the daily choice that flows from our new identity: *yield yourselves unto God, as those that are alive from the dead.* Having reckoned ourselves dead to sin and alive to God, we are now to yield ourselves, to present ourselves and our members, to God rather than to sin. This is the practical, daily outworking of our new identity, the choice of whom we will yield ourselves to, and it is a key to walking in victory.

Consider the two possibilities Paul sets before us. First, the negative: *Neither yield ye your members as instruments of unrighteousness unto sin.* We can yield our members, our bodies, our faculties, to sin, presenting them as instruments of unrighteousness, tools for sin to use. This is what we do when we give in to temptation, friend; we yield our members to sin, presenting ourselves as instruments for unrighteousness. And Paul tells us not to do this, not to yield ourselves to sin as its instruments. We have a choice about whom we yield ourselves to, and we are not to yield ourselves to sin.

And see the positive: *but yield yourselves unto God, as those that are alive from the dead, and your members as instruments of righteousness unto God.* Instead of yielding ourselves to sin, we are to yield ourselves to God, presenting ourselves and our members as instruments of righteousness for God to use. This is the choice we are to make, friend, the daily, moment-by-moment choice to yield ourselves to God rather than to sin, to present our members as instruments of righteousness rather than unrighteousness. We yield ourselves to God, offering ourselves to Him, as those who are alive from the dead.

Notice the basis on which we yield ourselves to God: *as those that are alive from the dead.* We yield ourselves to God on the basis of our new identity, as those who have been made alive from the dead through Christ. This connects to yesterday's reckoning, friend. Having reckoned ourselves dead to sin and alive to God, we now yield ourselves to God as those who are alive from the dead. The reckoning leads to the yielding; because we are alive from the dead, we yield ourselves to God. Our new identity is the basis for our daily choice to present ourselves to God rather than to sin.

So make this daily choice, friend, to yield yourself to God rather than to sin. Throughout each day, in the moments of temptation and decision, you are constantly yielding yourself to one or the other, presenting your members as instruments of unrighteousness to sin, or of righteousness to God. So choose, deliberately and daily, to yield yourself to God. When temptation comes, do not yield your members to sin as instruments of unrighteousness; instead, yield yourself to God, presenting your members as instruments of righteousness for Him to use. This is the practical outworking of your new identity, friend, the daily choice to yield yourself to God as one who is alive from the dead. So reckon yourself dead to sin and alive to God, and then yield yourself to God, presenting yourself and your members to Him as instruments of righteousness. For this daily yielding is a key to walking in victory, the practical choice that flows from your new identity in Christ.`,
    prayer: `Lord, having reckoned myself dead to sin and alive to God, help me now to yield myself to You. Throughout each day, in the moments of temptation and decision, I am constantly yielding myself to sin or to You. Help me to choose, deliberately and daily, to yield myself to You, presenting my members as instruments of righteousness rather than yielding them to sin as instruments of unrighteousness. As one who is alive from the dead, I yield myself to You, Lord. Use me for righteousness. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, make the daily choice to "yield yourselves unto God." In moments of temptation and decision, deliberately present your members as "instruments of righteousness unto God" rather than yielding them to sin as instruments of unrighteousness.`,
    reflect: `What does it mean to "yield yourself" to God rather than to sin, presenting your members as instruments of righteousness? How is this daily yielding the practical outworking of reckoning yourself "alive from the dead"?`,
  },
  {
    day: 26,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "The Victory Through Our Lord",
    ref: "1 Corinthians 15:57",
    scripture: "But thanks be to God, which giveth us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.",
    walk: `Friend, here Paul breaks into thanksgiving for the victory God gives, and the verse points us to the true source of all our victory over temptation: *thanks be to God, which giveth us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.* The victory is given by God, through our Lord Jesus Christ. It is not a victory we achieve by our own strength, but a victory God gives us through Christ. This reframes the entire battle, for it locates our victory not in ourselves but in Christ, and calls forth our thanksgiving.

Consider the source of the victory: *thanks be to God, which giveth us the victory.* The victory is given by God; it is His gift to us. This is crucial, friend, for it locates the source of our victory not in ourselves but in God. We do not achieve victory over temptation by our own strength, our own willpower, our own resolve; the victory is given to us by God. This reframes the entire battle. We are not striving to achieve a victory by our own efforts, hoping we might be strong enough; we are receiving a victory God gives, depending on Him for the triumph rather than on ourselves.

And see the means of the victory: *through our Lord Jesus Christ.* The victory God gives comes through our Lord Jesus Christ. It is through Christ, through His death and resurrection, through our union with Him, that God gives us the victory. Christ is the means of our victory, the one through whom God grants us the triumph. This is why we have spent this week fixing our eyes on Christ our victor, friend, for it is through Him that the victory comes. We do not overcome temptation apart from Christ, by some independent strength of our own; we overcome through Him, through our union with the victorious Christ.

Notice that Paul's response to this victory is thanksgiving: *thanks be to God.* Because the victory is God's gift through Christ, the fitting response is thanksgiving, gratitude, praise to God for the victory He gives. This is significant, friend. If the victory were our own achievement, we might be tempted to pride, to boasting in our own strength. But because the victory is God's gift through Christ, our response is thanksgiving, giving God the glory for the victory He gives us. The victory humbles us and calls forth our gratitude, for it is not our achievement but God's gift.

So locate your victory where it truly lies, friend, not in yourself but in Christ, and let it call forth your thanksgiving. When you overcome temptation, do not boast in your own strength, as though the victory were your achievement; give thanks to God, who gives you the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ. And when you face temptation, do not strive to achieve victory by your own strength, but depend on God to give you the victory through Christ. This reframes the entire battle, friend. The victory over temptation is not something you achieve, but something God gives, through our Lord Jesus Christ. So depend on Him for the victory, receive it as His gift, and give Him thanks for it. For thanks be to God, who gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ. The victory is His gift, friend, through Christ, so depend on Him for it, and give Him the thanks and glory it deserves.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thanks be to You, who gives me the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ. Help me to locate my victory where it truly lies, not in myself, but in Christ. When I overcome temptation, keep me from boasting in my own strength, and help me instead to give You thanks for the victory You give. And when I face temptation, help me not to strive to achieve victory by my own strength, but to depend on You to give me the victory through Christ. Thank You for the victory that is Your gift through my Lord Jesus Christ. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, locate your victory in Christ, not in yourself. When you overcome temptation, give thanks to God rather than boasting in your own strength; when you face it, depend on God to "give you the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ."`,
    reflect: `How does it reframe the battle to know that victory over temptation is something God "gives" through Christ, not something you achieve by your own strength? Why is thanksgiving the fitting response to a victory that is God's gift?`,
  },
  {
    day: 27,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Overcome by the Blood of the Lamb",
    ref: "Revelation 12:11",
    scripture: "And they overcame him by the blood of the Lamb, and by the word of their testimony; and they loved not their lives unto the death.",
    walk: `Friend, here Scripture reveals how God's people overcome the accuser and enemy, giving us the very weapons of our victory: *they overcame him by the blood of the Lamb, and by the word of their testimony; and they loved not their lives unto the death.* The saints overcome the enemy by the blood of the Lamb, by the word of their testimony, and by a wholehearted devotion that does not cling to this life. These are the means of overcoming, and they show us how the victory is won.

Consider the first means of victory: *by the blood of the Lamb.* The saints overcome the enemy by the blood of the Lamb, the blood of Christ shed for our sins. This is the foundation of all our victory, friend. When the enemy accuses us, when temptation assaults us, the blood of the Lamb is our answer, for it has paid for our sins and defeated the enemy. We overcome not by our own goodness or strength, but by the blood of the Lamb, which has conquered sin and the enemy. The blood of Christ is the first and foundational means of our overcoming.

Consider the second means: *by the word of their testimony.* The saints also overcome by the word of their testimony, by confessing and declaring the truth of what Christ has done, by testifying to His victory and their faith in Him. There is power in declaring the truth, friend, in speaking out our testimony of Christ's victory and our trust in Him. When we testify to what Christ has done, declaring the truth of the gospel against the lies of the enemy, we overcome. The word of our testimony, our confession of Christ's victory, is a means of overcoming the enemy.

Consider the third means: *they loved not their lives unto the death.* The saints overcame by a wholehearted devotion that did not cling to this life, that was willing even to die rather than to deny Christ or yield to the enemy. This is a wholehearted commitment, friend, a devotion to Christ so complete that it does not cling even to life itself. Those who love not their lives unto the death cannot be mastered by temptation that appeals to self-preservation and the love of this life. Their wholehearted devotion, holding nothing back, not even their lives, is a means of overcoming. The enemy has no hold on those who love not their lives unto the death.

So take up these means of victory, friend, that you might overcome the enemy and the temptations he brings. Overcome by the blood of the Lamb, resting on the blood of Christ, which has paid for your sins and defeated the enemy, answering every accusation and assault with the blood. Overcome by the word of your testimony, declaring the truth of Christ's victory and your faith in Him, speaking out the gospel against the lies of the enemy. And overcome by a wholehearted devotion that does not cling to this life, holding nothing back from Christ, willing even to die rather than to yield to the enemy. For these are the means by which the saints overcome, friend: the blood of the Lamb, the word of their testimony, and a devotion that loves not its life unto the death. So take them up, and overcome the enemy in the power of these mighty means, resting on the blood, declaring the testimony, and giving yourself wholly to Christ. For by these the saints overcame, and by these, in Christ's strength, so may you.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for revealing how Your people overcome the enemy: by the blood of the Lamb, by the word of their testimony, and by a devotion that loves not its life unto the death. Help me to overcome by these means. Let me rest on the blood of Christ, which has defeated the enemy. Let me declare the word of my testimony, speaking the truth of Your victory against the enemy's lies. And give me a wholehearted devotion that holds nothing back from You, not even my life. In these means, help me to overcome. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take up the three means by which the saints overcame: rest on "the blood of the Lamb," declare "the word of your testimony" against the enemy's lies, and give Christ a wholehearted devotion that holds nothing back, not even your life.`,
    reflect: `How do "the blood of the Lamb" and "the word of their testimony" serve as means of overcoming the enemy? What does it mean to overcome by a devotion that "loved not their lives unto the death," holding nothing back from Christ?`,
  },
  {
    day: 28,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "This Is the Victory, Even Our Faith",
    ref: "1 John 5:4",
    scripture: "For whatsoever is born of God overcometh the world: and this is the victory that overcometh the world, even our faith.",
    walk: `Friend, here John names the victory that overcomes the world, and it is a victory available to every believer: *this is the victory that overcometh the world, even our faith.* Our faith is the victory that overcomes the world. Those who are born of God overcome the world, and they do so by faith. This is wonderfully encouraging, friend, for it means that the victory over the world and its temptations is laid hold of by faith, which every believer has.

Consider the assurance John gives: *whatsoever is born of God overcometh the world.* Those who are born of God, every true believer, overcome the world. This is stated as a settled fact, friend. To be born of God is to be an overcomer; the new birth brings with it the capacity to overcome the world. Every believer, having been born of God, has this overcoming capacity, this victory over the world and its temptations. We are not destined to be overcome by the world; as those born of God, we overcome it.

And see what John identifies as the victory: *this is the victory that overcometh the world, even our faith.* The victory that overcomes the world is our faith. It is by faith that we overcome the world, faith in Christ, faith that lays hold of His victory, faith that trusts His promises and rests in His finished work. This is encouraging, friend, for faith is something every believer has. The victory over the world is not laid hold of by extraordinary strength, or remarkable willpower, or heroic effort, but by faith, which every believer possesses. By faith we overcome the world.

Consider how faith overcomes the world and its temptations, friend. The world tempts us with its lies, its false promises, its allurements, telling us that its pleasures will satisfy, that its way is best, that we must have what it offers. And faith overcomes these temptations by laying hold of a greater reality, the truth of God, the promises of Christ, the surpassing worth of knowing Him. Faith looks past the lies of the world to the truth of God, past the fleeting pleasures of sin to the lasting joy of Christ, and so it overcomes the world's allurements. By trusting God over the world, faith overcomes the world.

So lay hold of the victory by faith, friend, the victory that overcomes the world. You do not need extraordinary strength or remarkable willpower to overcome the world and its temptations; you need faith, which you have as one born of God. So exercise your faith in the battle against temptation. When the world tempts you with its lies and false promises, overcome by faith, laying hold of the truth of God, the promises of Christ, the surpassing worth of knowing Him. Trust God over the world, believe His promises over the world's allurements, rest in Christ's finished work, and so overcome the world by faith. For this is the victory that overcomes the world, friend, even your faith. So lay hold of it, exercise it, and overcome the world and its temptations by the faith that every believer born of God possesses. The victory is laid hold of by faith, so believe, and overcome.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You for the encouraging truth that the victory which overcomes the world is faith, which I have as one born of God. I do not need extraordinary strength or willpower to overcome the world and its temptations; I need faith. Help me to exercise my faith in the battle. When the world tempts me with its lies and false promises, help me to overcome by faith, laying hold of Your truth, Your promises, and the surpassing worth of knowing Christ. Let my faith be the victory that overcomes the world. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, lay hold of the victory by faith. When the world tempts you with its lies and false promises, overcome by faith, laying hold of God's truth and Christ's promises over the world's allurements, trusting God over the world.`,
    reflect: `How is it encouraging that the victory which overcomes the world is "our faith," which every believer born of God possesses? How does faith overcome the world's temptations by laying hold of God's truth over the world's lies?`,
  },
  {
    day: 29,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Stand Fast in the Faith",
    ref: "1 Corinthians 16:13",
    scripture: "Watch ye, stand fast in the faith, quit you like men, be strong.",
    walk: `Friend, as we near the end of our journey, Paul gives us a series of stirring commands that call us to steadfast perseverance in the battle: *Watch ye, stand fast in the faith, quit you like men, be strong.* These are commands for the long fight, calling us to vigilance, steadfastness, courage, and strength. For victory over temptation is not won in a single battle, but in a life of steadfast perseverance, standing fast in the faith.

Consider the first command: *Watch ye.* Once again we hear the call to watch, to be vigilant and alert, which has run through this whole book. The battle against temptation requires ongoing vigilance, friend, a continual watchfulness that does not grow careless or complacent. We must watch throughout the whole course of the battle, staying alert to the assaults of temptation, never letting down our guard. The call to watch is a call to ongoing vigilance in the long fight.

Consider the second command: *stand fast in the faith.* We are to stand fast, to hold our ground, to remain firm and steadfast in the faith. This is a call to steadfastness, friend, to standing firm and not being moved, to holding our ground in the faith against all the assaults that would shake us. We are not to waver, not to be moved, not to give ground, but to stand fast in the faith, remaining firm and steadfast through the long battle. Standing fast is the steadfast perseverance that holds its ground over the long course of the fight.

Consider the third and fourth commands: *quit you like men, be strong.* To quit ourselves like men is to act with courage and maturity, to conduct ourselves with the bravery and strength that the battle requires. And to be strong is to be strengthened, to find strength for the fight. These are calls to courage and strength, friend, to facing the battle with bravery and finding the strength we need to persevere. We are not to be timid or weak in the battle, but to quit ourselves like men, with courage and maturity, and to be strong, strengthened for the fight. Courage and strength are needed for the long perseverance.

So take up these commands for the long fight, friend, and persevere with steadfastness in the battle against temptation. Understand that victory is not won in a single battle, but in a life of steadfast perseverance, of ongoing vigilance, steadfastness, courage, and strength. So watch, staying alert and vigilant throughout the whole course of the battle, never growing careless. Stand fast in the faith, holding your ground, remaining firm and steadfast, not being moved. Quit yourself like a man, facing the battle with courage and maturity. And be strong, finding strength for the fight in the Lord. For the battle against temptation is a long one, friend, requiring steadfast perseverance, and these commands call us to that perseverance: to watch, to stand fast, to be courageous, to be strong. So take them up, and persevere in the long fight, standing fast in the faith, strong in the strength God provides, all the way to the end.`,
    prayer: `Lord, You call me to watch, to stand fast in the faith, to quit myself like a man, and to be strong. Help me to take up these commands for the long fight. I understand that victory over temptation is not won in a single battle, but in a life of steadfast perseverance. So help me to watch with ongoing vigilance, to stand fast in the faith without being moved, to face the battle with courage, and to be strong in Your strength. Help me to persevere in the long fight, standing fast all the way to the end. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, take up the commands for the long fight: "watch," "stand fast in the faith," "quit you like men," and "be strong." Embrace that victory comes through steadfast perseverance, and resolve to persevere with vigilance, steadfastness, courage, and strength.`,
    reflect: `Why is victory over temptation won through steadfast perseverance rather than a single battle? Which of these commands, to watch, stand fast, be courageous, or be strong, do you most need to take up for the long fight ahead?`,
  },
  {
    day: 30,
    week: 4,
    weekTitle: "Victory Through Christ",
    title: "Always Causeth Us to Triumph",
    ref: "2 Corinthians 2:14",
    scripture: "Now thanks be unto God, which always causeth us to triumph in Christ, and maketh manifest the savour of his knowledge by us in every place.",
    walk: `Friend, we have come to our final day, and we close with a triumphant note of thanksgiving that lifts our eyes to the certain victory God gives in Christ: *thanks be unto God, which always causeth us to triumph in Christ.* God always causes us to triumph in Christ. This is the glorious destination of our whole journey, friend, the assurance that, in Christ, our victory over temptation is not occasional or uncertain, but a triumph God always causes us to share. Let us close on this triumphant note.

Consider the sweeping assurance: *which always causeth us to triumph in Christ.* God always causes us to triumph in Christ. Notice the word *always*. This is not an occasional, uncertain victory, but a triumph God always causes us to share in Christ. The picture Paul draws is of a triumphal procession, in which the victorious general leads his people in the celebration of victory. And God always leads us in this triumph in Christ, causing us to share in the victory Christ has won. Our triumph is not uncertain or occasional; in Christ, God always causes us to triumph.

And see where this triumph is found: *in Christ.* The triumph is in Christ, in union with Him, sharing in His victory. This is the key, friend, the truth that has run through this whole final week. Our triumph over temptation is found not in ourselves, not in our own strength or achievement, but in Christ, in union with Him who has overcome. And in Christ, God always causes us to triumph. So long as we are in Christ, sharing in His victory, the triumph is certain, for it is His triumph in which we share. In Christ, God always causes us to triumph.

And see the wonderful result of this triumph: *and maketh manifest the savour of his knowledge by us in every place.* As God causes us to triumph in Christ, He spreads the sweet fragrance of the knowledge of Christ through us, everywhere we go. Our triumph over temptation, our victorious life in Christ, becomes a fragrance that spreads the knowledge of Christ to others. There is a wonderful purpose in our victory, friend. It is not for ourselves alone, but spreads the sweet savour of Christ's knowledge to the world around us, drawing others to the Christ who gives us the victory. Our triumph becomes a testimony, a fragrance, that makes Christ known.

So close this journey on this triumphant note, friend: in Christ, God always causes you to triumph. You came into these thirty days, perhaps, weary of defeat, discouraged by repeated failure, wondering whether victory was even possible. But you have seen that the victory is real, found not in your own strength but in Christ, who has overcome the tempter and now causes you to triumph. So fix your eyes on this certain triumph. In Christ, God always causes you to triumph over temptation, leading you in His victory procession, spreading the sweet fragrance of His knowledge through your victorious life. So do not return to the cycle of defeat and despair, friend, but walk in the triumph God gives you in Christ. For thanks be unto God, who always causes you to triumph in Christ. The victory is certain, friend, found in Christ, so walk in it, and let your triumphant life spread the sweet savour of His knowledge in every place. 🙏`,
    prayer: `Lord, thanks be unto You, who always causes me to triumph in Christ. What a glorious assurance to close this journey: that my victory over temptation is not occasional or uncertain, but a triumph You always cause me to share in Christ. Thank You that the victory is found not in my own strength, but in Christ, who has overcome. Help me to walk in this certain triumph, no longer returning to the cycle of defeat and despair, but living in the victory You give. And let my triumphant life spread the sweet savour of Christ's knowledge in every place. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
    oneThing: `Today, fix your eyes on the certain triumph: in Christ, God "always causeth us to triumph." Walk in this victory rather than returning to the cycle of defeat, and let your triumphant life spread "the savour of his knowledge" to those around you.`,
    reflect: `Looking back over these thirty days, how has your view of the battle against temptation changed, from defeat toward the triumph God gives in Christ? What does it mean that God "always" causes you to triumph "in Christ," and how might your victory spread "the savour of his knowledge" to others?`,
  },
];

